[CENTER][SIZE=7][B]LuminScope[/B][/SIZE]
[SIZE=5]Find out which plugin is lagging your proxy. In one command.[/SIZE]

[SIZE=4][B]Free · Open source (MIT) · Velocity 3.3+[/B][/SIZE][/CENTER]

[HR][/HR]

[SIZE=6][B]"The server is lagging"[/B][/SIZE]

That sentence can mean at least seven different things:

[LIST]
[*]The backend's tick loop is slow
[*]The proxy's garbage collector is pausing
[*]The link between proxy and backend is slow
[*]The player's own route is bad
[*]A plugin is blocking the network threads
[*]A database call is blocking
[*]The player's machine is struggling
[/LIST]

Today you guess. Spark profiles [B]backends[/B]. Plan measures [B]players[/B]. The proxy — the thing every single packet passes through — has had nothing at all.

[HR][/HR]

[SIZE=6][B]Why the proxy is the right place to measure[/B][/SIZE]

Because it is the only component that sees [B]both halves of the round trip at once[/B].

Only your proxy can say:

[QUOTE]This player is 15 ms away from me. But I am 180 ms away from survival-1.[/QUOTE]

That one sentence ends the investigation. No backend profiler and no player-side tool can produce it, because neither of them can see the other side.

[HR][/HR]

[SIZE=6][B]What you actually see[/B][/SIZE]

[CODE]/luminscope

--- LuminScope · Diagnosis ---
 [!] The proxy's I/O threads are being blocked
   Tasks are waiting up to 412 ms to run on the proxy's I/O threads
   (median 6 ms). While that happens, every packet on every backend is queued.
   The stack sampler caught SomeEconomyPlugin on an I/O thread 14 times,
   most recently at EconomyStorage.loadBalance:88.
   -> Start with SomeEconomyPlugin. Something in it is running a blocking
      call on the network thread - usually a synchronous database or HTTP
      request that belongs on the scheduler.[/CODE]

[B]Conclusions first, numbers second.[/B] Exporting metrics is the easy half and the less useful one — most operators cannot read a Grafana dashboard and should not have to.

[HR][/HR]

[SIZE=6][B]Name the plugin that is blocking your proxy[/B][/SIZE]

This is the feature people screenshot.

When an event loop stalls, the whole network stalls with it, and the proxy log says nothing. The usual outcome is an operator disabling plugins one at a time over a week.

LuminScope samples the I/O thread stacks the moment a stall happens, finds the topmost frame belonging to a plugin, and maps it back to that plugin's id. One command, one name, done.

Sampling only runs [B]during[/B] a stall, so the cost is paid exactly when it does not matter.

[HR][/HR]

[SIZE=6][B]Everything it measures[/B][/SIZE]

[SIZE=5][B]Event loop scheduling delay[/B][/SIZE]
The single most useful number on a proxy. A no-op task is submitted to the I/O threads and the wait before it runs is recorded. It is [I]measured[/I], not read off an internal field — so a Velocity update cannot silently break it. If the probe cannot attach, it falls back to scheduler timing, tells you plainly, and keeps working.

[SIZE=5][B]Latency, split three ways[/B][/SIZE]
Player-to-proxy, proxy-to-backend, and the full server switch broken into connect and total phases.

All in percentiles, never averages. If the median switch is 200 ms and the 99th percentile is eight seconds, one player in a hundred is convinced your network is dead — and the average will cheerfully report "0.3 s, all fine".

[SIZE=5][B]JVM internals[/B][/SIZE]
Heap, GC pause [I]counts[/I] rather than totals (one 400 ms stop-the-world hurts; four hundred 1 ms pauses do not), thread counts, and off-heap buffer usage. That last one matters because Netty buffer leaks are real and genuinely hard to find: the heap looks fine, the process keeps growing, and nothing in a normal profiler explains it.

[HR][/HR]

[SIZE=6][B]Self-healing (off by default)[/B][/SIZE]

LuminScope can take an unresponsive backend out of the routing rotation and put it back gradually.

It is off by default and deliberately timid when on, because [B]automation that fires at the wrong moment is worse than no automation[/B]. Draining a healthy server over a thirty-second blip turns a non-event into an outage.

[LIST]
[*]Never drains the last server standing
[*]Never touches anything on your protected list
[*]Eases traffic back over a ramp — a server that just recovered has cold caches and an empty pool, and the entire queued population arriving at once is how it dies a second time
[*]Logs and announces every single action
[/LIST]

[HR][/HR]

[SIZE=6][B]Commands[/B][/SIZE]

Permission [ICODE]luminscope.admin[/ICODE]. Aliases [ICODE]/lscope[/ICODE], [ICODE]/scope[/ICODE].

[LIST]
[*][ICODE]/luminscope[/ICODE] — findings: what is wrong and what to try
[*][ICODE]/luminscope latency[/ICODE] — client, backend and switch percentiles, per server
[*][ICODE]/luminscope jvm[/ICODE] — heap, GC, threads, off-heap, event loop delay
[*][ICODE]/luminscope blocking[/ICODE] — which plugins were caught on the I/O threads
[*][ICODE]/luminscope healing[/ICODE] — rotation status and manual restore
[*][ICODE]/luminscope reset[/ICODE] — clear counters, start measuring from now
[*][ICODE]/luminscope reload[/ICODE]
[/LIST]

[HR][/HR]

[SIZE=6][B]Prometheus and Discord[/B][/SIZE]

OpenMetrics endpoint with optional bearer token, bound to localhost by default. Discord webhook alerts with per-finding cooldowns, because posting the same alert every window guarantees the channel gets muted before anyone fixes anything.

[HR][/HR]

[SIZE=6][B]Overhead[/B][/SIZE]

This is an observability tool. If it slows your proxy down, it has failed.

[LIST]
[*]Stack sampling runs only during a stall, never on the happy path
[*]Latency lives in fixed-bucket histograms — a bounds check and an increment, roughly 6 KB each
[*]Backend pings are asynchronous and reuse the proxy's existing path
[*]Nothing runs on the I/O threads except the probe task, which is a no-op
[/LIST]

Under 1% of one core on a 500-player network. Check it yourself with [ICODE]/luminscope jvm[/ICODE] before and after.

[HR][/HR]

[SIZE=6][B]Requirements[/B][/SIZE]

Velocity 3.3.0+, Java 17+. No backend plugin. No shaded dependencies, so nothing to conflict with the rest of your stack.

[SIZE=6][B]Source[/B][/SIZE]

MIT licensed: [URL]https://github.com/lumin-mc/LuminScope[/URL]

Bug reports with console output get fixed quickly. Pull requests get merged.
